author: Heather_Barnett;
title: What humans can learn from semi-intelligent slime

aws-transcripts.transcript: I'd like to introduce you to an organism. A slime mold fight. Arum Polis, eh Phylum. It's a mould with an identity crisis, but it's not a mold, so let's get that straight to start with. It is one of 700 known slime molds belonging to the Kingdom of the Amoeba. It is a single celled organism, a cell that joins together with other cells to form a mess super cell to maximize its resources. So within a slime mould, you might find thousands or millions of nuclei, all sharing a cell wall, operating as one entity in its natural habitat. You might find the slime mould foraging in woodlands eating rotting vegetation, but you might equally find it in research laboratories, classrooms and even artist studios.
